%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ematernity%20leave%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThings%20weren't%20easier%20as%20he%20got%20older.%20Like%20many%20American%20parents%2C%20we%20struggled%20with%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fchildcare-costs-without-grandparents-help-millennial-parents-boomers-2024-10%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ecosts%20like%20childcare%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20which%20only%20increased%20when%20we%20had%20our%20daughter%20in%202021%20and%20our%20daycare%20costs%20more%20than%20doubled.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EA%20few%20months%20after%20she%20was%20born%2C%20a%20new%20opportunity%20arose%3A%20our%20family%20could%20move%20to%20Spain.%20My%20husband's%20job%20was%20expanding%20to%20Europe%2C%20and%20we%20saw%20this%20as%20an%20opportunity%20to%20move%20closer%20to%20his%20family.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%222610%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Emily%20San%20Jos%C3%A9%20with%20her%20husband.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F67ae67e47bb3f854015cdd3c%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221957%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EEmily%20San%20Jos%C3%A9%20with%20her%20husband.%3Cp%3EEmily%20San%20Jos%C3%A9%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3ESo%2C%20when%20my%20daughter%20was%20four%20months%20old%2C%20our%20family%20of%20five%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Ffamily-moving-from-new-york-to-madrid-for-a-year-2025-2%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Erelocated%20to%20Madrid%3C%2Fa%3E.%20Caring%20for%20a%20baby%20in%20each%20country%2C%20the%20differences%20are%20striking.%20While%20I%20miss%20a%20few%20things%20about%20the%20US%2C%20Spain%20makes%20raising%20kids%20so%20much%20easier%20and%20more%20affordable%20for%20families.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%2286948c6f-b89e-4817-a713-ce4420810efd%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EI%20wish%20I'd%20given%20birth%20in%20Spain%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EWhile%20I%20never%20gave%20birth%20in%20Spain%2C%20I've%20spoken%20to%20many%20moms%20who%20have.%20It's%20unheard%20of%20for%20pregnant%20women%20to%20work%20up%20until%20the%20last%20minute%2C%20as%20I%20did.%20In%20Spain%2C%20women%20usually%20take%20the%20last%20month%20as%20leave.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EPostpartum%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fmaternity-leave-in-europe-vs-us-2023-10%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ematernity%20leave%3C%2Fa%3E%20is%20also%20longer%3Cstrong%3E%20%3C%2Fstrong%3Ein%20Spain.%20The%20US%20is%20the%20only%20developed%20country%20not%20to%20offer%20guaranteed%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fmaternity-leave-around-the-world-2018-5%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Epaid%20parental%20leave%3C%2Fa%3E.%20In%20Spain%2C%20everyone%2C%20including%20fathers%2C%20is%20given%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Famerican-mom-in-spain-shares-differences-in-parental-leave-2024-8%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E16%20weeks%20of%20parental%20leave%3C%2Fa%3E.%20In%20addition%20to%20being%20fully%20paid%2C%20the%20money%20isn't%20taxed%2C%20so%20parents%20receive%20even%20more%20money%20than%20in%20their%20usual%20paychecks%20during%20that%20time%20as%20a%20way%20to%20support%20families.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhen%20they%20return%20to%20work%2C%20mothers%20get%20an%20hour%20a%20day%20of%20%26quot%3Blactation%20leave%2C%26quot%3B%20guaranteed%20by%20federal%20law%2C%20until%20their%20child%20is%20nine%20months%20old.%20If%20a%20mother%20has%20kids%20under%2012%2C%20she%20can%20also%20opt%20to%20request%20working%20reduced%20hours%20(with%20a%20pay%20cut).%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHaving%20so%20much%20flexibility%20means%20parents%20get%20to%20spend%20more%20time%20with%20their%20kids%20in%20the%20first%20few%20months%20of%20their%20lives.%20I%20wish%20I%20had%20more%20of%20that%20time%20with%20my%20kids%20when%20they%20were%20born%20in%20the%20US.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%22e973d8ad-5e4b-4127-a587-fdeec911a696%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EChildcare%20is%20much%20more%20affordable%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EWhen%20we%20lived%20in%20the%20US%2C%20we%20spent%20%241%2C800%20on%20daycare%20per%20month%20for%20our%20son.%20When%20we%20had%20our%20daughter%2C%20we%20added%20on%20%241%2C900%20for%20her%20spot%2C%20a%20little%20extra%20because%20she%20was%20an%20infant.%20That%20brought%20our%20monthly%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.youtube.com%2Fwatch%3Fv%3DXksv2EGG9ek%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Edaycare%20costs%3C%2Fa%3E%20to%20%243%2C700%20%E2%80%94%20more%20than%20our%20mortgage.%20Being%20on%20a%20teacher's%20salary%20and%20not%20making%20that%20much%2C%20I%20sometimes%20wondered%20if%20I%20should%20drop%20out%20of%20the%20workforce%20and%20become%20a%20stay-at-home%20mom%20instead%20of%20spending%20the%20money%20on%20daycare.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhile%20daycare%20isn't%20free%20in%20Spain%2C%20it's%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fi-moved-to-spain-for-more-affordable-childcare-2024-4%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ea%20lot%20more%20affordable%3C%2Fa%3E.%20We%20paid%20%E2%82%AC500%20for%20our%20daughter.%20For%20our%20son%2C%20who%20was%20old%20enough%20to%20start%20going%20to%20school%2C%20we%20chose%20to%20put%20him%20in%20the%20same%20private%20school%20his%20older%20brother%20attended%2C%20which%20cost%20%E2%82%AC300.%20For%20two%20young%20children%2C%20the%20total%20costs%20were%20%E2%82%AC800%2C%20or%20around%20%24830%20a%20month%2C%20which%20was%20easier%20for%20us%20to%20swing%20even%20with%20me%20taking%20a%20pay%20cut.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAdditionally%2C%20families%20with%20three%20or%20more%20children%20are%20entitled%20to%20a%20Tarjeta%20Familia%20Numerosa%2C%20or%20%26quot%3BLarge%20Family%20Card.%26quot%3B%20This%20card%20has%20given%20us%20many%20discounts%2C%20including%20on%20train%20tickets%2C%20groceries%2C%20electricity%20and%20water%20bills%2C%20and%20passport%20renewals.%20It%20helps%20us%20prevent%20small%20costs%20from%20snowballing.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%22a1e37150-2288-400e-ac02-5eb9b0b6e3af%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EIn%20Spain%2C%20kids%20are%20part%20of%20adult%20society%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%221024%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Emily%20San%20Jos%C3%A9%20with%20her%20daughter.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F67ae683beb4be2fff9a49f9e%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22768%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EEmily%20San%20Jos%C3%A9%20with%20her%20daughter.%3Cp%3EEmily%20San%20Jos%C3%A9%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3ESpain%20feels%20more%20family-friendly%20than%20the%20US%20because%20children%20are%20more%20integrated%20into%20adult%20society.%20While%20there%20are%20still%20some%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fchild-focused-parenting-bad-for-kids-parents-2024-7%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Echild-focused%20activities%3C%2Fa%3E%20like%20zoos%20and%20birthday%20parties%2C%20it's%20much%20more%20normal%20to%20see%20children%20in%20adult%20spaces%20like%20bars%20and%20restaurants.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThis%20starts%20at%20school.%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Famerican-living-in-spain-shares-differences-in-school-2023-11%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3ESpanish%20school%20lunches%3C%2Fa%3E%20include%20more%20adult%20meals%20like%20a%20vegetable%20pur%C3%A9e%20appetizer%2C%20a%20main%20like%20chicken%20or%20fish%20with%20rice%20or%20potatoes%2C%20and%20then%20fruit%20or%20yogurt%20for%20dessert.%20The%20kids%20are%20also%20taught%20table%20manners.%20Not%20only%20are%20they%20less%20picky%20%E2%80%94%20my%20three-year-old%20now%20likes%20salads!%20%E2%80%94%20but%20it's%20easier%20to%20bring%20kids%20to%20restaurants%20because%20they%20know%20how%20to%20behave%20in%20public.%20It's%20very%20common%20for%20kids%20to%20join%20their%20parents%20for%20dinner%2C%20staying%20up%20late%20with%20the%20grown-ups.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAdults%2C%20in%20tu